Your “checklist” of conditions for sustained, cumulative innovation—strong property rights, open debate, pluralism, rule of law, fluid capital markets, widely-disseminated education, incentives for both incremental work and high-risk breakthroughs—most closely maps onto the broad Enlightenment-liberal model of society. In practice that has taken the form of a constitutional state with market-based economics, individual rights protections, and a culture of toleration. More specifically:
1. Ideological Core: Classical or Enlightenment Liberalism • Political‐individualism — the idea that persons have inalienable rights (life, liberty, property) and that government exists to secure them. • Limited government — checks and balances, separation of powers, a written constitution or strong parliamentary traditions. • Free expression and open inquiry — academic and press freedom, legal protections for dissent. • Economic freedom — contract enforcement, open markets, low barriers to entry and exit for entrepreneurs.
2. Typical Government Form: • Constitutional Monarchy → Parliamentary Democracy – In 18th-century Britain you already had a powerful, elected Parliament and an independent judiciary. The monarch’s prerogatives were circumscribed by law. – Over the 19th and early 20th centuries this evolved toward fully responsible government (where the cabinet is answerable to an elected majority) and universal suffrage. • Federal Republic (in the Anglophone offshoots) – In the United States after 1789, the same liberal‐constitutional principles were applied in a federal‐republican form. States held significant powers, there was a written Bill of Rights, and the Supreme Court enforced individual liberties.
3. Why This Blend? – Rule of Law & Property Rights: Firms and inventors can invest in new tools and processes knowing the fruits won’t be arbitrarily seized. – Capital Formation: Public debt, joint-stock companies and a nascent banking sector let large sums underwrite coal mining, steam engines and canals. – Intellectual Pluralism: Religious toleration for non-Anglicans (Dissenters, Quakers, Catholics) and a rising merchant class produced wide participation in learned societies. – Open Communication: A relatively uncensored press, the Royal Society’s Philosophical Transactions, coffee-houses and salons let results—and even wild hypotheses—circulate rapidly.
In short, the “recipe” that best fits Britain’s mid-18th-century surge—and that recurs in other high-innovation societies—is a political-economic system built on Enlightenment liberalism, instantiated as a constitutional (proto-)democracy with strong market institutions and a culture of free inquiry.
Why did the growth rate of the summed significant innovation-impact-score decreased after 1750 and how to prevent that decline 

.
o4-mini




Several factors help explain why the rate at which “summed significance” climbed begins to taper off after the mid-18th century, even though the absolute number of innovators and discoveries stays high. Broadly speaking, it’s a story of diminishing returns, growing complexity, and institutional maturation. If you wanted to “prevent” the slowdown—i.e. rekindle the same blistering pace of ever-bigger breakthroughs—you’d need to address each of these head-on:
1. Low-Hanging Fruit Gets Picked • In the run-up to 1750, fundamental concepts and methods (classical mechanics, experimental chemistry, systematic taxonomy) were new. Each leap opened dozens of easy follow-on projects—“fruit” hanging low for investigators. • Once a field matures, the next breakthroughs require ever more sophisticated equipment, deeper theory, or larger collaborations. That makes each individual advance “costlier” in time and resources, so the rate of high-impact events slows.
How to push back: – Continually fund radically new fields (e.g. when quantum mechanics was young, it spawned dozens of table-top experiments). – Encourage blue-sky “moonshots” in areas that are still “pre-paradigmatic” (e.g. basic brain science, fusion energy, space-based physics).
2. Rising Scale and Complexity • Early science could often be done by a lone gentleman-philosopher with a telescope, a few lenses, a good library and a small workshop. By the mid-19th and 20th centuries, pushing frontiers often meant particle accelerators, supercomputers, or multi-institutional field surveys. • Big teams and big budgets mean longer ramp-up, slower decision cycles, and higher barriers to entry. This dampens the frequency of blockbuster results.
How to push back: – Maintain a healthy balance of small-team or individual grants alongside “big science” projects. – Lower administrative overhead (grant paperwork, compliance) so creative researchers spend more time actually researching.
3. Institutional Inertia & Professionalization • As universities, journals, grant agencies and professional societies crystallize best practices, they also enforce orthodoxies—sometimes discouraging radical challenges to the status quo. • Careers become increasingly risk-averse, because a failed “heretical” project can jeopardize tenure or funding.
How to push back: – Carve out protected funding streams for high-risk, high-reward work (e.g. DARPA’s model, X-prize or “skunkworks” labs). – Promote “failure tolerance” in academic and industrial R&D: publish null results, rotate reviewers, encourage post-tenure experimentation.
4. Diminishing “Signal-to-Noise” in Publication • The volume of journals, conferences and preprints has exploded. Finding genuinely groundbreaking work amidst the flood is harder, and high-impact ideas can get lost or delayed. • Metrics (citation counts, journal impact factors) can incentivize incremental “salami-slicing” rather than bold new paradigms.
How to push back: – Improve filtering: smarter peer review, machine-learning-backed article triage, open peer commentary. – Reward conceptual novelty explicitly in grant and promotion criteria.
5. Shifts from Individual to Collective Credit • As team sizes grow, it’s harder to single out one “giant.” Credit is dispersed. That may depress the apparent “impact score” per individual, even if the collective achievement is enormous. • Summed impact may still be rising, but averaged per name, it can flatten or fall.
How to push back: – Develop new ways of recognizing and rewarding distributed or cross-disciplinary breakthroughs (e.g. team prizes, lab awards). – Encourage career narratives that highlight roles (architect, strategist, builder) rather than just “first author.”
6. Societal and Economic Constraints • Wars, depressions, demographic transitions or resource bottlenecks can divert talent and capital into non-innovative priorities. • At some point, a society’s appetite for “progress” may run up against environmental limits or public skepticism (e.g. debates over GMOs, AI risk, climate geoengineering).
How to push back: – Insulate basic research budgets from short-term political cycles. – Foster public engagement and science literacy so that disruptive technologies maintain broad social legitimacy.
